concernsOpen: That because this is an online interaction with a patient, they might not actually take the advice given to them because the interaction wasn't a sincere human-human interaction where they could understand the importance of the care I would be prescribing. One of the questions also asked me about how much I assumed their job is requiring of them -- so in this case I'm wondering if I recommend Dave a certain form of treatment, he won't be able to actually follow through with that treatment that he needs. For example, the ideal treatment might be to take time off work for the week and rest (among other things), but if he can't spend a few days away from work and if his work requires him to do physical movement like heavy lifting, then that would be an issue in his recovery. So my biggest concern is how we can factor in realistic recovery to his exact lifestyle and needs.
treatmentWhy_1: I chose these pain options based off the process of elimination. Starting from Tier 4, I would definitely not recommend a surgical procedure because that carries high risk and is the most invasive of all the treatment options. And based off of just one symptom I cannot recommend a surgical procedure without more information. Tier 3 and Tier 2 includes different opiates, and I would definitely not recommend this to a patient that I haven't seen or to one that does not absolutely require them. This is because the potential for addiction is so high. I would start with Tier 1, the most minimally invasive and lowest threat option and see if it helps to alleviate the symptoms. If it doesn't then we can ask about more potential symptoms and think of other treatment options, like possibly the higher tiers. For now, I'm hoping the topical lidocane and acetaminophin will help enough. Also, doctors can prescribe high levels of acetaminophen for pain that are higher levels than can be found OTC but are still safe and effective.
treatmentWhy_2: Because Dave didn't have the chance to try out the initial treatment options that I recommended which were Tier 1 treatments, I recommended the exact ones again. I won't move on to the next Tier of treatment options until the previous ones have been tried/tested by the patient. Dave said he did not do these treatment options, so I will wait until he does.
moveForwardOpen: I would say clearly to Dave: how do you expect your symptoms to improve if you do not follow the treatment options? I would ask if there is something in his life situationally/environmentally that is hindering him getting help. If it is just genuinely because he forgot, then there is no one to blame but himself, and honestly now that I'm thinking about it the pain might not be that bad. And why would he be scheduling follow ups with me if he isn't taking my advice? Also, I would make sure to say thank you to Dave for being honest. I assume my patients don't normally tell me the truth when they haven't taken my advice.

notes_1:
'-Take all medications as directed. 
-Apply moist heat to the affected area for 10-15 minutes Q 2hrs PRN. 
-Perform stretches or see Physical Therapy as directed. 
-Take 600-800mg of ibuprofen 3 times daily maximum with food and water for 14 days. 
-Get any ordered imaging done before the next appointment 
-Try to identify triggers, things that make the pain worse or better, & keep a log of your these & pain levels daily & bring to every appointment. 
-Bring all prescription and over the counter medications youre taking to each appointment. 
-Be aware of signs of an emergent condition such as loss of bowel or bladder control, Saddle Paresthesia, loss of sensation, inability to move any part of your body, and severe pain not controlled with current medications and Care Plan.
-Return for next appointment as scheduled. 
-Return here, go to the closest appropriate Emergency Room, and/or call 911 if you think you need to.
notes_2:
'-Reinforce compliance with risks and benefits explain clearly. He will not get better if he doesnt try to follow the advice given to him. 
-Only use any habit forming medication for 3-7 days maximum & no more if he has had multiple prescriptions for controlled substances. 
-Have him sign a Controlled Substance Agreement and prescribe emergency naloxone you plan to prescribe any further controlled substances to him. 
-Try to identify the source of his pain with a thorough History and Examination with appropriate diagnostic testing if needed.
-Advise him of potential emergency warning signs to be aware of and to seek immediate treatment if any occur. 
-Start and bring pain log to each appointment with lists of triggers and alleviating factors. 
-Bring all medications especially any controlled substances to each appointment for pill counting. 
- Reinforce the use of proper body mechanics. 
-Encourage him to help you help him. This may give him a sense of empowerment over his health care decisions and motivation him to be more compliant.

treatmentWhy_1: When possible and appropriate, starting with more conservative treatment for low back pain is advisable. It appears this is a young relatively healthy patient whom the doctor is seeing for the first time. Without more history provided, we can't know if the patient has a substance use disorder or some other contraindications to opioids. Pluse, opioids do have significant risks. For most patients with low back pain, authoritative bodies recommend starting therapy with nonpharmacologic interventions (i.e. exercise, physical therapy) and nonopioid treatments (i.e. NSAIDs when not contraindicated). Thus, from the options provided, tylenol and the topical lidocaine were selected for safer alternatives to opioids for this patient.
treatmentWhy_2: The patient had noted that they were busy and hadn't really been able to comply with the therapies recommended at the prior visit. As the treating physician, I would want to understand more about the patient's pain and why they didn't follow through with the previously recommended treatment so that I could best help them. For example, were they unable to get the scripts filled due to an insurance coverage issue, did they have an adverse reaction to the medicine and discontinued use, etc. It's advisable to give more conservative treatments a concerted effort (perhaps for 4 to 6 weeks) before moving onto more invasive testing/procedures or stronger (perhaps riskier) medications. The lidocaine topical patch should be relatively safe and easy to use. The steroid injection may provide longer pain relief and help decrease inflammation.
moveForwardOpen: Ask if they would be willing to share if there were other circumstances in their life that could be impacting their health or their ability to follow the recommended treatments at this time in order to determine best how to help them.

notes_1:
Dave presents with constant, dull pain in his back. 

He was seen for a tele-health visit on two separate occasions. 

During his first (initial) visit, he was given the recommendation to take Tylenol and use a topical lidocaine treatment. 

At his follow-up visit, Dave reported that his pain remained the same. He also reported that due to time constraints, he did not follow the recommended treatment plan. Recommended that Dave first try Tylenol and the topical lidocaine as first line therapy for his pain and to ensure that he takes the medication as prescribed so that we can accurately assess whether this treatment plan is sufficient to alleviate his pain or if we need to move up to a second tier pain medication.
notes_2:
Dave returned for a second follow-up appointment to re-evaluate his treatment plan for constant, dull low back pain. 

During our visit today, Dave states he has not had any changes in his pain level. He also report that he has not followed his treatment plan. He stated it slipped his mind. 

After re-evaluating his pain severity. We discussed the importance of following the prescribed treatment plan in order to determine if this was working to alleviate his pain. We also had a conversation about how realistic it is that he can follow this treatment plan with his lifestyle and if there were any barriers that he could identify. We also set goals and expectations for managing his pain levels with his current treatment plan.
